<reference id="image" xml:lang="en-us">
<title><xmlelement>image</xmlelement></title>
<shortdesc>Use the <xmlelement>image</xmlelement> element to include artwork or images in a DITA
    topic.</shortdesc>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>accessibility<indexterm>images</indexterm></indexterm><indexterm>images<indexterm>alternate
            text</indexterm><indexterm>overview</indexterm><indexterm>placement</indexterm><indexterm>size</indexterm></indexterm>
        <indexterm>elements<indexterm>body<indexterm><xmlelement>image</xmlelement></indexterm></indexterm></indexterm>
</keywords>
</metadata></prolog>
<refbody>
    <section id="section-1">
      <p>The <xmlelement>image</xmlelement> element has an optional <xmlatt>placement</xmlatt>
        attribute that indicates whether the included graphic or artwork <ph 
          >is rendered inline</ph> (a button or icon) or on a separate line for a larger image.
        There also are attributes that indicate the size to which the included graphic or artwork
          <ph >is</ph> scaled.</p>
      <p>An image element specifies an <xmlatt>href</xmlatt> attribute, a <xmlatt>keyref</xmlatt>
        attribute, or both. When both <xmlatt>keyref</xmlatt> and <xmlatt>href</xmlatt> are
        specified, the <xmlatt>href</xmlatt> is used as a fallback when the key reference cannot be
        resolved. The image addressed by the <xmlatt>keyref</xmlatt> or <xmlatt>href</xmlatt> is
        brought into the main flow of the content as rendered. </p>
      <p>To make the intent of the image more accessible for users using screen readers or text-only
        readers, authors should include a description of the image content in the <xmlelement>alt</xmlelement> element.</p>
    </section>
